Model

In[]:
knots = np.quantile(data.month_encoded, [0.25, 0.5, 0.75])

# Define the B-splines using the knots
bs = BSplines(data[['month_encoded']], df = [4], degree = [3])

# Fit the GLM model with the B-splines as exog
gam_model = GLMGam.from_formula('resolution_time ~ 1', data = data, smoother = bs)
gam_result = gam_model.fit()

# Print the summary of the model
print(gam_result.summary())

Cross-Validation

In[]:
# Define the cross-validation strategy
cv = KFold(n_splits = 5, random_state = 82, shuffle = True)

# Use cross_val_score to perform cross-validation
scores = cross_val_score(LinearRegression(), data[['month_encoded']], data['resolution_time'], scoring = 'neg_mean_squared_error', cv = cv)

# The cross_val_score function returns negative MSE scores, so take the negative of the scores
mse_scores = -scores

# Calculate the average MSE across all folds
average_mse = np.mean(mse_scores)
print(f'Average MSE from cross-validation: {average_mse}')

Average MSE from cross-validation: 20028125.52042725

The value of p-value is less than 0.05 suggesting a strong relationship with the resolution time at these points. However, the p-value of month_encoded_s2 is greater than 0.05 shows that this spline term does not significantly improve the model's fit to the data.

The cross-validation MSE is quite high, which might suggest that while the model finds a statistically significant relationship within the data it was trained on, its predictions are not very close to the actual values when tested on unseen data.

# Plot the map with points colored by case type

# Assuming 'data' is your DataFrame and has 'longitude' and 'latitude' columns

# Define the limits of the map around San Francisco's coordinates
sf_bbox = {
    'left': -122.5149,
    'bottom': 37.7081,
    'right': -122.3494,
    'top': 37.8110
}

# Create a simple scatter plot
